Step 1: Create the directory

Weâ€™ll put the script inside /opt/lexcorp:

sudo mkdir -p /opt/lexcorp

ðŸ”¹ Step 2: Create the script file

Open it with a text editor like nano:

sudo nano /opt/lexcorp/monitor.sh


Now paste this inside:

#!/bin/bash
while true; do
  echo "----- $(date) -----" >> /var/log/resource.log
  top -bn1 | head -5 >> /var/log/resource.log
  free -h >> /var/log/resource.log
  ifconfig eth0 >> /var/log/resource.log
  sleep 60
done


Save in nano by pressing:

CTRL + O â†’ Enter (to write file)

CTRL + X (to exit)

ðŸ”¹ Step 3: Make it executable
sudo chmod +x /opt/lexcorp/monitor.sh

ðŸ”¹ Step 4: Test it manually

Run:

sudo /opt/lexcorp/monitor.sh &


The & runs it in background.

Wait 1â€“2 minutes, then check:

tail -n 20 /var/log/resource.log


You should see timestamp, CPU, memory, and network details.

ðŸ”¹ Step 5: Automate with cron

Edit cron:

crontab -e


Add this line at the bottom:

@reboot /opt/lexcorp/monitor.sh &


Save and exit.

âœ… This makes the script start automatically whenever the system boots.

ðŸ”¹ Deliverable (what to submit)

